  "prompt": "How can I define bijection between (0,1) and (0,1]?",
  "response": "To define a bijection between (0,1) and (0,1] involves finding a function that pairs each element in (0,1) with a unique element in (0,1], and vice versa. Here's a step-by-step method to construct such a function:\n\n1. **Understand the Sets**:\n   - \\((0,1)\\): This is the interval of real numbers greater than 0 and less than 1.\n   - \\((0,1]\\): This is the interval of real numbers greater than 0 and less than or equal to 1.\n\n2. **Initial Idea for Bijection**:\n   - A bijection means for every \\( x \\in (0,1) \\) there is a unique \\( y \\in (0,1] \\) and vice versa.\n\n3. **Constructing a Function**:\n   - To achieve this, split the interval \\((0,1)\\) into two parts and map one part directly and the other part using a transformation involving 1.\n\nHere is a more concrete construction method:\n\n- Define \\(f : (0,1) \\to (0,1]\\) in the following way:\n  - For \\( x \\in (0, 0.5) \\), let \\( f(x) = x \\).\n  - For \\( x \\in [0.5, 1) \\), let \\( f(x) = 2x - 1 \\).\n\nThis function essentially maps the first half of the interval directly to itself and the second half to the subinterval \\((0.5, 1]\\).\n\n- **Verify Bijectiveness**:\n  - For \\( x \\in (0, 0.5) \\), since \\( f(x) = x \\), it is clearly bijective (identity function).\n  - For \\( x \\in [0.5, 1) \\), if \\( y = 2x - 1 \\):\n    - \\( x = (y + 1) / 2 \\), hence it is bijective as each element there maps uniquely.\n\n- **Combining these into one function**:\n  \\( f(x) = \\begin{cases} \n      x & \\text{if } x \\in (0, 0.5) \\\\ \n      2x - 1 & \\text{if } x \\in [0.5, 1) \n     \\end{cases} \\)\n\nTherefore, \\( f \\) is a bijection from \\((0,1)\\) to \\((0,1]\\).\n\nIf you want every \\(x \\in (0,1]\\) to map to a unique value in \\((0,1)\\):\n\n- Define \\( g: (0,1] \\to (0,1) \\):\n  - For \\( y \\in (0,0.5] \\), let \\( g(y) = y / 2 \\).\n  - For \\( y \\in (0.5, 1] \\), let \\( g(y) = (y + 1) / 2 \\).\n\nThis function maps one interval directly into \\( (0, 0.5) \\) and the other into \\((0.5, 1)\\).\n\n- **Verify Bijectiveness**:\n  - For \\( y \\in (0,0.5] \\), \\( g(y) = y / 2 \\): it is bijective.\n  - For \\( y \\in (0.5, 1] \\), \\( g(y) = (y + 1) / 2 \\): each \\( y \\) maps uniquely as in reverse of earlier.\n\nTherefore, \\( g \\) provides a unique pairing and fulfills the requirement of a bijection from \\( (0,1] \\) to \\( (0,1) \\).\n\nSo, combining both definitions:\n\\[ f : (0,1) \\to (0,1] \\text{ and } g: (0,1] \\to (0,1) \\]\nwhere:\n\\[ f(x) = \\begin{cases} \n      x & \\text{if } x \\in (0, 0.5) \\\\ \n      2x - 1 & \\text{if } x \\in [0.5, 1) \n     \\end{cases} \\]\n\n\\[ g(y) = \\begin{cases} \n      y / 2 & \\text{if } y \\in (0, 0.5] \\\\ \n      (y + 1) / 2 & \\text{if } y \\in (0.5, 1] \n     \\end{cases} \\]\n\nBoth together create a bijection between (0,1) and (0,1].",
